{"key":"processedPost-12765138","value":{"id":12765138,"first":12764964,"last":12765340,"when":1276905784,"utime":"06/19/10 03:03 AM","content":"A 20F rise in temperature cuts the humidity in half. . . .temporarily.&nbsp; <br /><br />I'd put the light(s) above and in front of the terrarium.&nbsp; A foot or so away shouldn't produce too much heat.&nbsp; As the temperature rises somewhat, it creates an area with less dense air within the terrarium.&nbsp; This less dense air in turn causes 'more dense' air within the perlite to rise, thus drawing in fresh air from the bottom, replenishing the humidity.&nbsp; <br /><br />To understand this concept, you have to forget the 'hot air rises' mantra our first grade teachers pounded into our heads.&nbsp; This is an exception.&nbsp; Air flows from high pressure to low pressure, or from more dense air to less dense air, regardless of temperature.<br /><br />After an hour or two, the humidity should stabilize.&nbsp; At any rate, during the time the humidity is dropping, it triggers evaporation of moisture from the substrate, which is a major pinning trigger.<br /><br />One important thing to also consider is hygrometer placement.&nbsp; If you have it on the sides against the holes, the incoming air will influence the reading. Place the hygrometer in the center of the terrarium, sitting on the perlite or a piece of foil, like the cakes.<br />RR","title":"Re: Proper lighting seems to counteract high humidity. Help!"}}